-- State landlord/tenant law seed — batch (generated by genStateLawSeed.ts).
-- Sourced from official .gov statutes 2026-06-11; every value cited + independently verified
-- against the quoted statute text before seeding. Provisions attach to each state's 'residential'
-- act; a topic absent for a state = no statutory value exists (NOT invented). Hedged + dated +
-- disclaimered at surface time per the S442 posture. States: WI, IA, AR, MS, KS, NM, NE, ID, WV, HI.
--
-- SOURCING NOTES (nuances the figures alone don't capture — read before relying on a value):
-- [WI] RESIDENTIAL ACT: Wisconsin's residential landlord-tenant rules live in two complementary bodies — the statute (Wis. Stat. ch. 704) and the DATCP administrative code (Wis. Admin. Code ch. ATCP 134, adopted under Wis. Stat. § 100.20). The concrete numeric residential rules (entry notice, late-fee constraint) appear in ATCP 134, while deposit/termination rules appear in both. I cited the most specific source for each value.
-- [WI] OMITTED PROVISIONS (no statutory value — not invented):
-- [WI] - deposit_max_months: Wisconsin imposes NO cap on the maximum security deposit. Neither Wis. Stat. § 704.28 nor ATCP 134.06 limits the dollar/months amount; ATCP 134.02(12) only defines that any prepaid rent exceeding one month is treated as a security deposit. No maximum exists, so this topic is omitted.
-- [WI] - late_fee_max_pct: Wisconsin does NOT cap late fees by percentage or amount. ATCP 134.09(8)(a) only requires that any late fee be expressly provided in the rental agreement (\"No landlord may charge a late rent fee or late rent penalty to a tenant, except as specifically provided under the rental agreement\"). No statutory percentage cap exists, so omitted.
-- [WI] - late_fee_grace_days: Wisconsin statutes/code specify no mandatory grace period before a late fee may apply. Omitted.
-- [WI] ENTRY NOTICE nuance: The statute itself (Wis. Stat. § 704.05(2)) only requires \"advance notice ... at reasonable times\" with no stated number. The concrete 12-hour minimum comes from the administrative code (ATCP 134.09(2)(a)2.), which is the operative residential rule — that is the value reported.
-- [WI] UNIT-TYPE COVERAGE notes:
-- [WI] - Chapter 704 expressly governs BOTH residential tenancies and nonresidential (commercial) tenancies (§ 704.07(1) distinguishes them; defaults apply to nonresidential absent a contrary signed writing) — hence commercial is mapped to ch. 704. ATCP 134 applies to residential dwelling units only.
-- [WI] - rv_spot (long-term RV): Wisconsin has NO separate long-term-RV landlord-tenant act. A recreational vehicle/manufactured home occupied long-term in a 3+-plot community falls under the manufactured/mobile home community framework of § 710.15 (which references mobile, manufactured homes, and recreational vehicles used as dwellings sited on rented plots). Short-term recreational camping/campgrounds are licensed separately under Wis. Admin. Code ch. ATCP 79 (a health/safety licensing regime, not a landlord-tenant act) and are not included here. A standalone RV pad rented short-term would otherwise fall back to ch. 704 as a periodic tenancy.
-- [WI] - storage: Self-service storage is not governed by ch. 704's tenancy rules; it has its own lien statute at § 704.90.
--
-- [IA] RESIDENTIAL ACT = Iowa Code ch. 562A (Uniform Residential Landlord and Tenant Law); governs apartments and standard single-family residential dwellings. § 562A.5 excludes transient hotel/motel occupancy, agricultural-purpose rentals, institutional residences, condo/co-op owners, and contract-of-sale occupants.
-- [IA] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute does not specify, so no value invented):
-- [IA] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED. § 562A.9(4) caps late fees only as fixed DOLLAR amounts, not a percentage of rent. Tiered: rent <= $700/mo -> late fee cannot exceed $12/day or $60/mo total; rent > $700/mo -> cannot exceed $20/day or $100/mo total. There is no percentage-of-rent cap in the statute. Quote: "For rental agreements in which the rent does not exceed seven hundred dollars per month, a rental agreement shall not provide for a late fee that exceeds twelve dollars per day or a total amount of sixty dollars per month."
-- [IA] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. Ch. 562A imposes no statutory grace period before a late fee may be charged; rent is "payable without demand or notice at the time and place agreed upon" (§ 562A.9(3)). No grace-day minimum exists in the act.
-- [IA] ACT COVERAGE NOTES:
-- [IA] - rv_spot: Iowa has NO dedicated RV-park long-term tenancy act. Ch. 562B is limited to mobile/manufactured homes -- § 562B.7(6) defines "mobile home" as a vehicle WITHOUT motive power (and excludes motorized vehicles registered as motor vehicles in Iowa), so a typical RV does not qualify. RV long-term spots therefore fall outside both 562A and 562B and default to general lease/contract law (ch. 562). Membership campgrounds are separately addressed by ch. 557B (not a tenancy act). Mapped rv_spot to ch. 562 as the residual default; a landlord-configurable approach is appropriate since no on-point statute governs RV-spot tenancies.
-- [IA] - commercial: No URLTA-style act exists for commercial; governed by general ch. 562 (Owner-Lessor and Tenant-Lessee) plus contract terms.
-- [IA] - storage: Ch. 578A (Self-Service Storage Facility Lien) governs the lien/sale process; § 578B/SF528-era language confirms storage space may not be used for residential purposes. It is a lien statute, not a habitability/tenancy act -- none of the six residential provisions apply.
-- [IA] All residential provision values were read directly from the official Iowa Legislature PDF statute text (Iowa Code 2026 printing, footer-dated Dec 2025), not secondary sources.
--
-- [AR] OFFICIAL SOURCE: Statute text verified against the full Arkansas Residential Landlord-Tenant Act of 2007 (Chapter 17, all sections), extracted from PDF and read line-by-line. The authoritative state site is the Arkansas General Assembly (arkleg.state.ar.us) code search; per-section deep links there are JS-driven and not stable, so sourceUrl points to verbatim-text mirrors (eForms-hosted full Chapter 17 PDF; FindLaw for Chapter 16 sections) whose language matches the statute exactly. officialUrl on each act points to the arkleg.state.ar.us code search.
-- [AR] ACT STRUCTURE: Two distinct landlord-tenant frameworks. (1) Chapter 17 = Residential Landlord-Tenant Act of 2007 — the operative residential act. Its definition of \"dwelling unit\" (§ 18-17-301(3)(A)) expressly \"includes landlord-owned mobile homes,\" and it covers single-family residences (§ 18-17-301(14)) and multi-unit/apartment dwellings. (2) Chapter 16 = general Landlord and Tenant provisions; its Subchapter 3 (§§ 18-16-301–306) is the ONLY statewide security-deposit law, and Chapter 17 § 18-17-501 expressly defers to § 18-16-301 et seq. for whether a deposit is required and all deposit rights/remedies — so the deposit cap and 60-day return live in Chapter 16 but are the residential deposit rules. § 18-16-111 governs tenant-owned manufactured/mobile homes on leased lot land (mobile-home-park lot rentals where the resident owns the home).
-- [AR] DEPOSIT LAW SCOPE LIMITATION (important for the DB): The Chapter 16 deposit subchapter does NOT apply to small landlords. § 18-16-303: \"This subchapter shall not apply to dwelling units owned by an individual, if the individual, his or her spouse and minor children, and any ... entities ... own, or collectively own, five (5) or fewer dwelling units\" — unless management/rent collection is done by a third party for a fee. So the 2-month cap and 60-day return bind only landlords with six (6) or more dwelling units (or who use a paid third-party manager). Encode the deposit provisions with that conditional applicability.
-- [AR] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute specifies NO value — not invented):
-- [AR] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. Chapter 17 § 18-17-602 (\"Access\") is the only access provision; it imposes a duty on the TENANT (\"A tenant shall not unreasonably withhold consent to the landlord to enter into the dwelling unit ...\") and sets NO advance-notice period, no hours, for the landlord. Arkansas statute does not require landlord entry notice.
-- [AR] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED. No late-fee cap anywhere in Chapter 17 or 16. \"Late charges\" appear only inside the definition of \"Rent\" (§ 18-17-301(10)), which is not a cap.
-- [AR] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. No statutory grace period before a late fee may apply. (Note: § 18-17-701(b) gives a 5-day window before the landlord may TERMINATE for nonpayment — that is an eviction-notice period, not a late-fee grace period, so it is not encoded here.)
-- [AR] OTHER NOTICE PERIODS (context, not requested topics): week-to-week tenancy termination = 7 days (§ 18-17-704(a)); tenant noncompliance/cure = 14 days (§ 18-17-701(a)); nonpayment-of-rent termination right = 5 days (§ 18-17-701(b)).
