-- [MS] Source of record: statutory text verified word-for-word against the Mississippi Attorney General's published edition of the Residential Landlord and Tenant Act (Miss. Code Ann. §§ 89-8-1 through 89-8-29), https://attorneygenerallynnfitch.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Residential-Landlord-and-Tenant-Act.pdf. The official Mississippi Code is published by the Legislature via Michie/LexisNexis (advance.lexis.com); Justia mirrors the same official code text and is used here as the durable, directly-fetchable citation URL.
-- [MS] ACTS: Mississippi has a SINGLE residential statute — the Residential Landlord and Tenant Act (Title 89, Chapter 8), applying to "any rental agreement entered into after July 1, 1991 ... for a dwelling unit located within this state" (§ 89-8-3). There is NO separate mobile-home-park act and NO separate RV-park / manufactured-home-community tenancy act in Mississippi. Manufactured/mobile-home lot rentals fall under the same residential act (the Act and its eviction sections repeatedly reference disposition of a tenant's "manufactured home," e.g. § 89-8-13(6), § 89-7-31(2)). Title 75 Ch. 49 / Admin Code Title 19 Pt. 7 govern only construction/installation standards for factory-built homes, NOT tenancy — excluded as non-landlord-tenant. The general chapter Title 89, Chapter 7 supplies the eviction machinery (notice to quit § 89-7-23, holdover/3-day-notice eviction § 89-7-27, summons/judgment §§ 89-7-29 to 89-7-49) and covers commercial / non-residential tenancies. Transient hotel/motel occupancy is expressly excluded from the residential act (§ 89-8-3 / Act intro, exclusion 4). For unit-type mapping: rv_spot is tagged on the residential act as the closest fit for long-term RV-lot tenancy since no RV-specific act exists; short-term/nightly RV stays would be 'transient occupancy' outside the act entirely.
-- [MS] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute specifies NO value — not invented):
-- [MS] - deposit_max_months: OMITTED. Mississippi imposes NO statutory cap on security-deposit amount. § 89-8-21 governs deposits but caps only bad-faith RETENTION damages: "The retention by a landlord ... in violation of this section and with absence of good faith, may subject the landlord ... to damages not to exceed Two Hundred Dollars ($200.00) in addition to any actual damages." That $200 is a penalty, not a deposit cap.
-- [MS] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED. No maximum late fee. The Act treats late fees as part of "rent": § 89-8-7(1)(h) "'Rent' means all payments to be made to the landlord under the rental agreement, including any late fees that are required to be paid under the rental agreement by a defaulting tenant" — but sets no percentage limit. Late fees are landlord-configurable via the rental agreement.
-- [MS] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. No statutory grace period before a late fee may apply.
-- [MS] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. Mississippi's Act contains NO landlord right-of-entry or advance-entry-notice provision at all. § 89-8-23 (Landlord Duties) and § 89-8-25 (Tenant Duties) impose no entry-notice obligation; the statute is silent on landlord entry, so no minimum notice exists.
-- [MS] For reference (statutory, but outside the six requested topics): material-noncompliance cure/termination notice is 14 days (§ 89-8-13(3)); nonpayment-of-rent eviction requires only a 3-day notice (§ 89-7-27 "Second"); tenant repair-and-deduct remedy capped at one month's rent after 30 days' written notice (§ 89-8-15); week-to-week tenancy termination notice is 7 days (§ 89-8-19(2)).
--
-- [KS] Source: Kansas Revisor of Statutes (ksrevisor.gov) and Kansas State Legislature (kslegislature.gov), Chapter 58.
-- [KS] ACTS: Kansas has no standalone commercial-tenancy act and no RV/recreational-vehicle-specific act in Chapter 58. (1) Residential Landlord and Tenant Act, K.S.A. 58-2540 ("This act shall be known and may be cited as the 'residential landlord and tenant act.'") governs standard residential dwelling units (apartments, single-family). (2) Mobile Home Parks Residential Landlord and Tenant Act, K.S.A. 58-25,100 et seq., governs mobile/manufactured homes in parks of two or more occupied mobile homes; "mobile home" includes manufactured homes per 58-4202. RVs are NOT defined or covered by this act (no "recreational vehicle" definition appears in 58-25,103) — rv_spot is therefore not mapped to any Kansas act. (3) Self-Service Storage Act, K.S.A. 58-814 et seq. ("As used in the self-service storage act"), governs storage; 58-815 prohibits residential use of storage spaces.
-- [KS] RESIDENTIAL ACT PROVISIONS — OMITTED (not in statute, not invented):
-- [KS] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. K.S.A. 58-2557 requires only entry "at reasonable hours, after reasonable notice to the tenant" — no specific hour count is given.
-- [KS] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED. The Residential Landlord and Tenant Act contains no late-fee/late-charge cap. (Note: a $20/month-or-20% late-fee limit exists ONLY in the Self-Service Storage Act, K.S.A. 58-816a, which is a different act and does not apply to residential tenancies.)
-- [KS] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. No grace-period provision exists in the residential act.
-- [KS] deposit_max_months note: the unfurnished cap is 1 month (used here). Furnished units allow up to 1.5 months, plus an additional 0.5 month if pets are permitted, per 58-2550(a).
-- [KS] notice_to_vacate_days note: 30 days standard; a 15-day exception applies for tenants in U.S. military service when termination is necessitated by military orders (58-2570).
--
-- [NM] Residential act = Uniform Owner-Resident Relations Act (UORRA), NMSA 1978 §§ 47-8-1 to 47-8-52; governs "dwelling units" (apartments + single-family standard residential). UORRA expressly does NOT cover commercial premises (applies only to dwelling units), so no commercial provisions are returned and no commercial act is listed (New Mexico has no dedicated commercial landlord-tenant statute; commercial tenancies fall under common law / general property law).
-- [NM] Mobile Home Park Act (§§ 47-10-1 to 47-10-23) governs space tenancies in mobile home parks (12+ occupied mobile homes for profit); UORRA also applies to park residents except where the MHPA directly conflicts. RV long-term: New Mexico has NO dedicated RV-park act. A "mobile home" under § 47-10-2 is a manufactured/transportable dwelling, not a recreational vehicle, so pure RV-spot tenancies arguably fall outside the MHPA and default to UORRA/common law. rv_spot is mapped to the MHPA only as the nearest park-tenancy statute; treat this mapping as soft, not a clean statutory fit.
-- [NM] Storage = Self-Service Storage Lien Act, Chapter 48 (Liens and Mortgages), Art. 11, §§ 48-11-1 to 48-11-9 — a lien/enforcement statute (5-day access denial, 90-day default before sale), not a full landlord-tenant relations act.
-- [NM] DEPOSIT CAP NUANCE (important): § 47-8-18 does NOT impose a universal hard cap. The 1-month cap is a true hard cap ONLY for rental agreements of a duration LESS than one year (§ 47-8-18(A)(2): "shall not demand or receive ... in excess of one month's rent"). For ANNUAL (one-year or longer) agreements there is NO maximum deposit amount; the statute instead requires the owner to pay annual passbook-rate interest on any deposit exceeding one month's rent (§ 47-8-18(A)(1)). Returned deposit_max_months=1 reflects the short-term hard cap, which is the only statutory months-of-rent maximum; the value is conditional, not absolute.
-- [NM] LATE FEE: § 47-8-15(D) caps the late fee at 10% of the total rent payment "for each rental period that the resident is in default," and only if the rental agreement provides for a late fee. The statute specifies NO grace period (no minimum number of days before a late fee may apply) — late_fee_grace_days is therefore OMITTED (not invented). To assess the fee the owner must give notice no later than the last day of the next rental period following the default.
-- [NM] Subsection letters on citations (§ 47-8-24(B), 47-8-18(C), 47-8-15(D), 47-8-37(B)) reflect the typical published subdivision; verify exact subsection letter against the official NMSA codification (nmonesource.com) as subdivision lettering can shift with amendments. Source URLs point to aanm.org's full reproduction of the act because the official mirrors (Justia, FindLaw, nmcourts.gov PDF, rld.nm.gov PDF) blocked automated retrieval (HTTP 403/301); all six values were cross-confirmed against multiple independent reproductions of the statutory text. Official statute home: New Mexico One Source (nmonesource.com, NM Compilation Commission) and nmlegis.gov.
--
-- [NE] Source: official Nebraska Legislature site (nebraskalegislature.gov), statute text verified directly.
-- [NE] RESIDENTIAL ACT = Uniform Residential Landlord and Tenant Act (URLTA), §§ 76-1401 to 76-1449. Governs apartments and standard single-family residential dwellings. § 76-1408 excludes occupancy under a contract of sale, transient hotel/motel occupancy, and premises used primarily for agricultural purposes, among others.
-- [NE] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute is silent — not invented): late_fee_max_pct and late_fee_grace_days are NOT addressed anywhere in the residential act. Nebraska imposes no statutory cap on late fees and no mandatory grace period; these are left to the rental agreement. Both correctly omitted per instructions.
-- [NE] UNIT TYPE MAPPING:
-- [NE] - mobile_home: Mobile Home Landlord and Tenant Act (§§ 76-1450 to 76-14,111) governs mobile home PARKS — the tenant owns the mobile home and rents the SPACE. (§ 76-1450: 'Sections 76-1450 to 76-14,111 ... may be cited as the Mobile Home Landlord and Tenant Act.')
-- [NE] - rv_spot: Nebraska has NO dedicated RV-park statute. Long-term RV-space rentals have no exact statutory home; the Mobile Home Landlord and Tenant Act is the nearest analog (space-rental model). Flagged as best-fit, not an explicit statutory match — confirm if a precise RV designation is required.
-- [NE] - commercial: Nebraska has NO dedicated commercial landlord-tenant statute. Commercial leases are governed by common law and contract terms, not a codified act. No act returned for commercial.
-- [NE] - storage: Disposition of Personal Property Landlord and Tenant Act (Chapter 69, §§ 69-2301 to 69-2314) — defines 'Landlord' and 'Premises' to include self-service storage units/facilities; governs disposition of personal property / lien-style remedies rather than a full residential-style tenancy framework.
-- [NE] Section titles for reference: § 76-1416 'Security deposits; prepaid rent; pet deposit'; § 76-1423 'Access'; § 76-1437 'Periodic tenancy; holdover; remedies'; § 76-1408 'Exclusions from application of act'.
--
-- [ID] Idaho has no single codified "residential landlord-tenant act." The operative residential provisions are scattered: Title 6, Ch. 3 (Forcible Entry and Unlawful Detainer) houses eviction procedure plus the security-deposit statute (§ 6-321) and tenant repair/damages remedies (§ 6-320, 6-323); Title 55, Ch. 3 (Rights and Obligations of Owners) houses the fee-reasonableness limit (§ 55-305) and the no-rent-control rule (§ 55-306); Title 55, Ch. 2 (§ 55-208) governs at-will/month-to-month termination notice.
-- [ID] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute specifies no value — not invented):
-- [ID] - entry_notice_hours: Idaho has NO statutory landlord entry-notice requirement. The commonly cited "24 hours" is a lease/best-practice convention, not statute. Omitted.
-- [ID] - deposit_max_months: § 6-321 imposes NO cap on security deposit amount. Omitted.
-- [ID] - late_fee_max_pct: § 55-305 only requires that "[a]ny fees imposed on a residential tenant, including fees for the late payment of rent, shall be reasonable" — no percentage cap. Omitted.
-- [ID] - late_fee_grace_days: No statutory grace period before a late fee may apply. Omitted.
-- [ID] deposit_return_days nuance: § 6-321(2) sets a default of 21 days when no time is fixed by agreement, but an absolute outer maximum of 30 days "in any event" after surrender. The 30-day figure is the binding statutory maximum and is what is recorded.
-- [ID] RV / rv_spot coverage: There is NO separate Idaho RV-park act. The Manufactured Home Residency Act (Title 55, Ch. 20) covers manufactured/mobile homes and — "for purposes of this chapter only" — park model recreational vehicles on rented lots, but standard recreational vehicles fall outside its scope (§ 55-2003 definition of "home"). General/transient RV-spot rentals therefore default to general property and contract law, not a dedicated statute, so rv_spot is not mapped to a specific act. storage units likewise have no landlord-tenant act mapping here (Idaho self-storage liens sit in a separate Title 55 chapter not covered by this residential research).
-- [ID] § 55-305 fee provision (full): "Any fees imposed on a residential tenant, including fees for the late payment of rent, shall be reasonable." An owner may not charge a fee/fine/interest greater than agreed in the rental agreement, or not included in the agreement, except on 30-day written notice (or oral agreement). Source: https://legislature.idaho.gov/statutesrules/idstat/title55/t55ch3/sect55-305/
--
-- [WV] Researched from official site code.wvlegislature.gov.
-- [WV] RESIDENTIAL ACT is split across two articles that operate together: Art. 6 (Landlord and Tenant — habitability/duties at §37-6-30, termination notice at §37-6-5, reentry/distress) and Art. 6A (Residential Rental Security Deposits — §§37-6A-1 to 6). The residential act applies to dwelling units; §37-6-31 only excludes squatter occupancy.
-- [WV] PROVISIONS DELIBERATELY OMITTED (verified the statute specifies NO value — not invented):
-- [WV] - entry_notice_hours: West Virginia has NO statutory landlord entry-notice requirement. §37-6-30 (landlord duty to maintain) contains no entry-notice provision and no other section establishes one.
-- [WV] - deposit_max_months: WV statute does NOT cap the security deposit amount. §37-6A-2 governs handling/return only, not size.
-- [WV] - late_fee_max_pct: WV does NOT cap late fees. §37-6A-2(b) only permits deducting \"reasonable charges for late payment of rent specified in the rental agreement\" — no percentage cap.
-- [WV] - late_fee_grace_days: no statutory grace period exists.
-- [WV] deposit_return_days = 60 is the outer bound. §37-6A-2(a) requires return \"within the applicable notice period\"; §37-6A-1(7) defines that as the SHORTER of 60 days from termination OR 45 days after a subsequent tenant occupies. When no new tenant moves in, 60 days is the governing maximum. (Note: a contractor-needed exception in §37-6A-2(c) allows an additional 15-day period to provide itemization.)
-- [WV] notice_to_vacate_days = 30: §37-6-5 requires \"notice for one full period\" to end a periodic tenancy; for month-to-month this is one month (~30 days). Year-to-year tenancies require 3 months. §37-6-5 also notes this default yields to a contrary \"special agreement.\"
-- [WV] UNIT-TYPE COVERAGE NOTES:
-- [WV] - rv_spot: NOT covered by any WV act. There is no recreational-vehicle / RV-park statute, and Art. 15 is limited to factory-built homes (house trailers, mobile, manufactured, modular) on a \"continual, nonrecreational basis\" — recreational use is expressly outside it. No act emitted for rv_spot.
-- [WV] - commercial: WV has no dedicated commercial-tenancy act. The older general provisions of Art. 6 (rent recovery, distress, reentry, eminent domain) apply to leases generally, but the residential habitability (§37-6-30) and security-deposit (Art. 6A) provisions are residential-only. Not emitted as a separate act because there is no distinct commercial statute.
-- [WV] - storage: Self-Service Storage Lien Act (ch. 38, art. 14) is a lien/enforcement statute, not a landlord-tenant habitability act.
--
-- [HI] SOURCING: capitol.hawaii.gov is Cloudflare-blocked to automated fetch, so text was verified against the official Hawaii Legislature PDF mirror (data.capitol.hawaii.gov/sessions/.../HRS_0521.pdf) plus the 2025 official codification cross-check on each section. The capitol.hawaii.gov URLs above are the canonical official statute pages.
-- [HI] MOBILE_HOME / RV: Hawaii has NO separate manufactured-home-community or RV-park act (unlike NH 205-A, CT ch.412, etc.). HRS § 521-7 (Exclusions) does NOT exclude mobile/manufactured homes or RVs; a mobile/manufactured home or a long-term RV used as a 'dwelling unit' (§ 521-8: 'a structure, or part of a structure, which is used as a home, residence, or sleeping place') is governed by Chapter 521. Excluded from 521 are only: institutional/incidental residence, university/dorm housing, contract-of-sale occupancy, fraternal-org housing, transient hotel/motel (day-to-day), employee/pensioner conditional occupancy, 15+ yr improved-land leases, prospective-purchaser occupancy, and homeless-program facilities. Day-to-day transient RV/hotel stays would fall under the § 521-7(5) transient exclusion, but long-term RV-spot tenancies are covered.
-- [HI] PROVISIONS OMITTED (not specified by statute): late_fee_grace_days — § 521-21(f) caps the late charge at 8% but specifies NO mandatory grace period; grace is purely a matter of the rental agreement. Deposit cap of 1 month is the general security deposit (§ 521-44(b)); a SEPARATE additional pet deposit of up to one month's rent is permitted under the same subsection (assistance animals exempt) but that is not the general deposit cap.
-- [HI] CITATION HISTORY: § 521-21(f) late-fee cap was added by Act 179, SLH 2017 — it is in the current code but NOT in pre-2017 versions. Both landlord (45-day) and tenant (28-day) month-to-month termination notices exist under § 521-71; notice_to_vacate_days uses the landlord-side 45-day figure (§ 521-71(a)). § 521-21(d) also requires 45 days' written notice for a rent increase on a month-to-month tenancy.
-- [HI] COMMERCIAL: Chapter 666 governs nonresidential summary possession; where Chapter 521 applies (residential) it controls. STORAGE: Chapter 507 Part II self-service-storage lien provisions (owner's lien attaches after rent unpaid 15 consecutive days; § 507-70 governs self-storage contracts).
--

